{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b31c11b7-5e40-4238-949c-84533ac144d5","content":"To switch to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC), you need to make these changes:\n\n**1. On nuget.org:**\n- Go to your package's settings → Trusted Publishers\n- Add a GitHub Actions publisher (owner, repo, branch/environment, workflow file)\n\n**2. In your GitHub Actions workflow:**\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write  # Required for OIDC token\n      contents: read\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n\n      # Build/pack your package...\n\n      - name: Push to NuGet\n        run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg\n          --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Key differences:**\n- Add `permissions: id-token: write` to the job\n- Remove `--api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }}` from the push command\n- No secret needed — the OIDC token is exchanged automatically\n- Consider using a GitHub Environment for additional protection (required if you configured one in the trusted publisher settings)\n\n**3. Cleanup (optional):**\n- Delete the `NUGET_API_KEY` repository secret once verified\n\nThe `dotnet nuget push` CLI automatically detects and uses the OIDC token when no API key is provided and the `id-token` permission is granted.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"de0b82fe-db8a-4ebe-8d57-478a064eb7f7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about switching from using a NuGet API key (stored as a secret) to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) in their GitHub Actions publish workflow. This is a general knowledge question about GitHub Actions and NuGet publishing - I don't need to look at any specific files since there's no repository here.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about what needs to change.","outputTokens":437,"requestId":"243D:204067:164E46F:18E1CDC:6A051F07"},"id":"48b18b1d-2de8-480a-85f1-74741543efa7","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:02:09.449Z","parentId":"f7660869-4b